## 1. Enum via Datatype

Dafny models enumerations as datatypes with nullary constructors:

```dafny
datatype OrderStatus = Created | PaymentPending | Paid | Shipped | Delivered | Cancelled | Refunded

datatype Role = Admin | Manager | Owner | Viewer | Author | Contact
```

Each constructor is a distinct value. Pattern matching is exhaustive — the compiler forces you
to handle every case. No integer mapping or abstract sig needed.

## 2. Type Aliases

Give semantic meaning to primitive types without wrapping overhead:

```dafny
type UserId = nat
type PlanId = nat
type PlatformAId = nat
type Day = int
type TzOffset = int
```

Prevents accidental mixing of ID types in function signatures. Lightweight — no runtime cost.

## 3. Record Datatypes

Model entities as immutable records with named fields:

```dafny
datatype User = User(id: UserId, deleted: bool)
datatype Plan = Plan(id: PlanId, published: bool)
datatype Subscription = Subscription(
  owner: UserId,
  plan: PlanId,
  status: SubStatus,
  obsolete: bool,
  platform: Platform
)
```

Fields are accessed with dot notation: `sub.owner`, `sub.status`. Datatypes are immutable —
create a new value to represent a state change.

## 4. Disjoint Union

Model an entity that belongs to exactly one of several categories using a tagged variant:

```dafny
datatype Platform = PlatformA(aId: PlatformAId) | PlatformB(bId: PlatformBId)
```

Must discriminate before accessing variant-specific fields:

```dafny
predicate isPlatformA(p: Platform) { p.PlatformA? }

function platformAId(p: Platform): PlatformAId
  requires p.PlatformA?
{ p.aId }
```

The `p.PlatformA?` test returns true if `p` was constructed with the `PlatformA` constructor.
Replaces Alloy's `extends` subtype pattern.

## 5. Helper Predicates

Partition the domain into named groups for reuse across access rules and invariants:

```dafny
predicate terminal(s: TaskState) { s == Done || s == Cancelled }
predicate editable(s: TaskState) { s == Draft || s == Review || s == Paused }

predicate isRequired(f: Field) { f == Title || f == Description || f == Priority || f == Deadline }
predicate isInternalOnly(f: Field) { f == CostBreakdown || f == InternalNotes || f == BillingRef }
predicate isActiveAllowed(f: Field) { f == Priority || f == Deadline || f == Attachments }
```

These predicates are pure, composable, and reusable. They replace Alloy's `fun` returning sets
(e.g., `fun internalOnly: set Field`).

## 6. Pure Functions with Postconditions

Specify function behavior via `ensures` without implementing full logic:

```dafny
function dayShift(offset: TzOffset): int
  requires validOffset(offset)
  ensures -1 <= dayShift(offset) <= 1
{
  if offset >= 12 then 1
  else if offset <= -12 then -1
  else 0
}
```

The `ensures` clause is the contract — lemmas can reason about it without knowing the body.
Replaces Alloy's `fun` with added verification power.

## 7. Total Ordering via Index Function

Dafny has no built-in `util/ordering`. Encode total order as a function mapping to `nat`:

```dafny
function stepIndex(s: Step): nat {
  match s {
    case S1_Trigger     => 0
    case S2_LoadContext  => 1
    case S3_Clarify     => 2
    case S4_SelectStyle => 3
    case S5_WriteModel  => 4
    // ...
  }
}

predicate stepBefore(a: Step, b: Step) { stepIndex(a) < stepIndex(b) }
predicate stepAtOrBefore(a: Step, b: Step) { stepIndex(a) <= stepIndex(b) }
```

This gives `<`, `<=`, `first`, `last` for free via integer comparison. The index function
is total (every variant has a mapping) so the ordering is complete.

## 8. Relation as Predicate

Encode Alloy's binary/ternary relations as predicates with exhaustive pattern matching:

```dafny
predicate ValidTransition(from: OrderStatus, to: OrderStatus) {
  (from == Created && to == PaymentPending) ||
  (from == PaymentPending && to == Paid) ||
  (from == Paid && to == Shipped) ||
  (from == Shipped && to == Delivered) ||
  (from == Created && to == Cancelled) ||
  (from == PaymentPending && to == Cancelled) ||
  (from == Paid && to == Cancelled) ||
  (from == Paid && to == Refunded)
}
```

The explicit enumeration of all valid pairs lets Dafny prove properties by exhaustive evaluation.
Replaces Alloy's `pred` with `sig` atoms and relational constraints.

## 9. Production Rule Dictionary

Map each artifact to its unique producer as a total function:

```dafny
function producedBy(a: Artifact): Step {
  match a {
    case RawData       => S1_Trigger
    case Validated     => S2_Validate
    case Enriched      => S3_Enrich
    case IndexData     => S4_Index
    case Report        => S5_Report
  }
}
```

Every artifact has exactly one producer (totality enforced by exhaustive match).
Replaces Alloy's `producedBy: one Step` field with a pure function.

## 10. System State as Aggregate

Encapsulate entire system state as a single datatype for invariant checking:

```dafny
datatype SystemState = SystemState(
  users: seq<User>,
  plans: seq<Plan>,
  subs: seq<Subscription>
)
```

All invariants take `SystemState` as input. Allows composing invariants into a single
`ValidState(st)` predicate. Replaces Alloy's implicit global scope.

## 11. Existence Query via Sequence Search

Replace Alloy's relational lookups with quantified sequence search:

```dafny
predicate userExists(st: SystemState, uid: UserId) {
  exists i :: 0 <= i < |st.users| && st.users[i].id == uid
}

predicate userDeleted(st: SystemState, uid: UserId) {
  exists i :: 0 <= i < |st.users| && st.users[i].id == uid && st.users[i].deleted
}

predicate planPublished(st: SystemState, pid: PlanId) {
  exists i :: 0 <= i < |st.plans| && st.plans[i].id == pid && st.plans[i].published
}
```

Always bound the quantifier: `0 <= i < |collection|`. This pattern replaces Alloy's
`some u: User | u.email = e` with explicit index bounds.

## 12. Uniqueness Constraint

Assert no two distinct elements share a property — mirrors SQL `UNIQUE WHERE`:

```dafny
predicate PlatformAUnique(st: SystemState) {
  forall i, j :: 0 <= i < |st.subs| && 0 <= j < |st.subs| && i != j ==>
    !(st.subs[i].platform.PlatformA? &&
      st.subs[j].platform.PlatformA? &&
      st.subs[i].platform.aId == st.subs[j].platform.aId &&
      !st.subs[i].obsolete &&
      !st.subs[j].obsolete)
}
```

The double quantifier with `i != j` checks all distinct pairs. The negation says "this
combination is impossible." Replaces Alloy's `lone { s: Sig | condition }`.

## 13. Referential Integrity

Enforce cascade constraints between parent and child entities:

```dafny
predicate NoLiveSubForDeletedUser(st: SystemState) {
  forall i :: 0 <= i < |st.subs| ==>
    (!st.subs[i].obsolete ==>
      !userDeleted(st, st.subs[i].owner))
}
```

Reads as: "for every live (non-obsolete) subscription, the owner is not deleted."
Replaces Alloy's `fact NoLiveSubForDeletedUser { all u: User | ... }`.

## 14. Composite Invariant Predicate

Bundle all system invariants into one predicate for easy use in lemma preconditions:

```dafny
predicate ValidState(st: SystemState) {
  NoLiveSubForDeletedUser(st) &&
  PlatformAUnique(st) &&
  PlatformBUnique(st) &&
  LiveStatusImpliesLive(st) &&
  ActiveSubRequiresPublishedPlan(st)
}
```

Lemmas require `ValidState(st)` instead of listing individual invariants. When you add
a new invariant, all lemmas automatically include it.

## 15. Transition Matrix

Model a state machine as an explicit transition predicate. All valid edges are enumerated:

```dafny
predicate ValidTransition(from: FlagStatus, to: FlagStatus) {
  (from == Draft && to == Staged) ||
  (from == Staged && to == Active) ||
  (from == Staged && to == Draft) ||       // rollback
  (from == Active && to == Deprecated) ||
  (from == Deprecated && to == Archived) ||
  (from == to)                             // stutter (stay in place)
}
```

Exhaustive enumeration means Dafny can prove properties by evaluating all cases.
The last line `(from == to)` adds an explicit stutter step (see pattern 20).

## 16. State with History

Track the previous state alongside the current state for single-step reasoning:

```dafny
datatype Order = Order(status: OrderStatus, previousStatus: OrderStatus)

predicate ValidOrder(o: Order) {
  (o.status == Created && o.previousStatus == Created) ||
  (o.status != Created && ValidTransition(o.previousStatus, o.status))
}
```

Allows proving properties like "if status is X, the previous state must have been Y"
without full trace reasoning. Lighter than a full sequence when only one step of history matters.

## 17. Executable Transition Methods

Dafny methods are verified AND compilable. A transition method carries proof obligations:

```dafny
method TransitionOrder(current: OrderStatus, target: OrderStatus)
  returns (result: Order)
  requires ValidTransition(current, target)
  ensures result.status == target
  ensures result.previousStatus == current
  ensures ValidOrder(result)
{
  result := Order(target, current);
}
```

This produces executable code (compiles to C#/Java/Go/JS) with correctness guaranteed by
the verifier. Replaces Alloy's `pred` transitions which are specifications only.

## 18. Chained State Progression

Chain transition methods to model a complete workflow:

```dafny
method ProcessOrder() returns (finalOrder: Order)
  ensures finalOrder.status == Delivered
{
  var o1 := TransitionOrder(Created, PaymentPending);
  var o2 := TransitionOrder(o1.status, Paid);
  var o3 := TransitionOrder(o2.status, Shipped);
  finalOrder := TransitionOrder(o3.status, Delivered);
}
```

Each step inherits the previous step's postcondition as the next step's precondition.
The final `ensures` proves the entire chain reaches the target state.

## 19. Branching Flows

Model alternative paths through the state machine with preconditions:

```dafny
method CancelOrder(fromStatus: OrderStatus) returns (result: Order)
  requires fromStatus == Created || fromStatus == PaymentPending || fromStatus == Paid
  ensures result.status == Cancelled
{
  result := TransitionOrder(fromStatus, Cancelled);
}
```

The `requires` clause enumerates valid source states. Dafny proves the transition is
valid for each allowed source.

## 20. Stutter Step

Include self-transitions in the transition matrix to allow "no change" steps:

```dafny
predicate ValidTransition(from: FlagStatus, to: FlagStatus) {
  // ... real transitions ...
  (from == to)  // stutter: system stays in current state
}
```

Without stutter, trace-based proofs may fail because the solver can't construct traces
of the required length. Stutter lets the system "wait" at any state. Replaces Alloy's
`pred stutter { frameUsers and frameSubs }`.

## 21. Trace as Sequence

Model temporal behavior as a sequence of states with adjacency constraints:

```dafny
predicate ValidTrace(trace: seq<OrderStatus>) {
  |trace| >= 1 &&
  trace[0] == Created &&
  forall i :: 0 <= i < |trace| - 1 ==> ValidTransition(trace[i], trace[i+1])
}
```

This is the fundamental encoding for temporal reasoning in Dafny. Every adjacent pair must
be a valid transition. The initial state is fixed. Replaces Alloy's `fact Init` + `fact Transitions`.

## 22. Always / Eventually via Quantifiers

Translate Alloy's temporal operators to quantifiers over trace indices:

```dafny
// Alloy: always P
// Dafny:
predicate alwaysHolds(trace: seq<OrderStatus>, P: OrderStatus -> bool) {
  forall i :: 0 <= i < |trace| ==> P(trace[i])
}

// Alloy: eventually P
// Dafny:
predicate eventuallyHolds(trace: seq<OrderStatus>, P: OrderStatus -> bool) {
  exists i :: 0 <= i < |trace| && P(trace[i])
}

// Alloy: P until Q
// Dafny:
predicate holdsUntil(trace: seq<OrderStatus>, P: OrderStatus -> bool, Q: OrderStatus -> bool) {
  exists j :: 0 <= j < |trace| && Q(trace[j]) &&
    forall i :: 0 <= i < j ==> P(trace[i])
}
```

The key difference: Alloy's temporal operators work on infinite traces with lasso structure;
Dafny works on finite sequences with explicit bounds. Dafny proofs are unbounded in sequence
length (proves for ALL valid traces), whereas Alloy checks within scope N.

## 23. Inductive Proof over Trace Indices

Prove temporal properties by induction on trace index with a `decreases` metric:

```dafny
lemma ArchivedIsForever(trace: seq<FlagStatus>, i: int)
  requires ValidTrace(trace)
  requires 0 <= i < |trace|
  requires trace[i] == Archived
  ensures forall j :: i <= j < |trace| ==> trace[j] == Archived
  decreases |trace| - i
{
  if i < |trace| - 1 {
    // ValidTransition(Archived, trace[i+1]) forces trace[i+1] == Archived
    ArchivedIsForever(trace, i + 1);  // inductive step
  }
}
```

Structure: base case (last index — trivial), inductive step (current state constrains next,
recurse on i+1). The `decreases |trace| - i` proves termination. This pattern replaces
Alloy's `always` assertions for sink/absorbing states.

## 24. Sink State Verification

Prove a state has no outgoing transitions except to itself:

```dafny
lemma ArchivedIsSink(from: FlagStatus, to: FlagStatus)
  requires from == Archived
  requires ValidTransition(from, to)
  ensures to == Archived
{ }
```

Empty body — Dafny evaluates `ValidTransition(Archived, to)` exhaustively and confirms only
`to == Archived` satisfies it. Combine with inductive trace proof (pattern 23) to get
"once archived, always archived."

## 25. Witness Trace Construction

Prove existence of a valid trace by constructing one explicitly:

```dafny
lemma FullLifecycleExists()
  ensures exists trace :: ValidTrace(trace) && |trace| == 6
    && trace[4] == Archived
{
  var trace := [Draft, Staged, Active, Deprecated, Archived, Archived];
  assert ValidTrace(trace);
}
```

The SMT solver can struggle with existentials. Providing an explicit witness (the `var trace`)
lets the solver verify rather than search. The final `assert` discharges the existential.

```dafny
// Multi-path witness: prove alternative paths exist
lemma RollbackThenActivateExists()
  ensures exists trace :: ValidTrace(trace) && |trace| == 5
    && trace[2] == Draft && trace[4] == Active
{
  var trace := [Draft, Staged, Draft, Staged, Active];
  assert ValidTrace(trace);
}
```

## 26. Trace Safety

Prove that once a certain state is reached, another state is unreachable:

```dafny
lemma CancelledBlocksShipping(trace: seq<OrderStatus>)
  requires ValidTrace(trace)
  ensures forall i, j :: 0 <= i < j < |trace| &&
    trace[i] == Cancelled ==> trace[j] != Shipped
{
  // Cancelled is a sink — ValidTransition(Cancelled, x) only allows x == Cancelled
}
```

Combines sink state reasoning with trace quantification. The solver evaluates all
transitions from Cancelled and confirms none lead to Shipped.

## 27. Role x State x Field Access Matrix

Encode field-level permissions as a three-argument predicate with cascading conditions:

```dafny
predicate canWrite(r: Role, s: TaskState, f: Field) {
  (r == Admin) ||                                                 // unrestricted
  (r == Manager && (editable(s) || (s == Active && isActiveAllowed(f)))) ||
  (r == Owner && !isInternalOnly(f) && editable(s)) ||
  (r == Author && s == Draft && !isInternalOnly(f))
  // Viewer, Contact: no branch → always false
}

predicate canRead(r: Role, f: Field) {
  !(r == Viewer && isInternalOnly(f))  // viewers can't see internal fields
}
```

Absence of a branch for a role means that role always gets `false`. Lemmas extract
security properties:

```dafny
lemma ViewerCannotWrite(s: TaskState, f: Field)
  ensures !canWrite(Viewer, s, f)
{ }

lemma AllRequiredFieldsSettable(f: Field)
  requires isRequired(f)
  ensures canWrite(Owner, Draft, f)
{ }
```

## 28. Role-Gated Transitions

Layer authorization on top of the state machine graph:

```dafny
predicate canTransition(r: Role, from: TaskState, to: TaskState) {
  validTransition(from, to) &&
  match (from, to) {
    case (Draft, Review) => r == Owner || r == Author || r == Admin
    case (Review, Active) => r == Manager || r == Admin
    case (_, Cancelled) => r == Owner || r == Admin
    case _ => r == Manager || r == Admin
  }
}
```

Two layers: `validTransition` checks the graph structure, the `match` checks role permission.
Both must hold for the transition to be allowed.

## 29. CTA Availability

Map call-to-action buttons to predicates over role and state:

```dafny
predicate ctaAvailable(cta: Cta, r: Role, s: TaskState) {
  (cta == CtaView) ||
  (cta == CtaApprove && (r == Manager || r == Admin) && s == Review) ||
  (cta == CtaReject && (r == Manager || r == Admin) && s == Review) ||
  (cta == CtaEstimate && canWrite(r, s, CostBreakdown))
}
```

Each CTA maps to a specific capability check. Proves which roles see which buttons in which states.

## 30. Notification Template Design

Model two layers: which states trigger a template, and which CTAs appear per role:

```dafny
predicate templateTriggeredInState(tmpl: NotificationTemplate, s: TaskState) {
  (tmpl == CostChange && (s == Draft || s == Review)) ||
  (tmpl == StatusUpdate) ||  // all states
  (tmpl == ApprovalRequest && s == Review)
}

predicate templateHasCta(tmpl: NotificationTemplate, cta: Cta, r: Role) {
  (tmpl == ApprovalRequest && cta == CtaApprove && (r == Manager || r == Admin)) ||
  (cta == CtaView)  // always present
}
```

Combine with CTA availability (pattern 29) to verify no dead buttons in notification emails.

## 31. Axiomatic Function

Specify behavior via postconditions when the full implementation is too complex or irrelevant:

```dafny
function dayShift(offset: TzOffset): int
  requires validOffset(offset)
  ensures -1 <= dayShift(offset) <= 1
{
  if offset >= 12 then 1
  else if offset <= -12 then -1
  else 0
}

function localDay(utcDay: Day, offset: TzOffset): Day
  requires validOffset(offset)
{
  utcDay + dayShift(offset)
}
```

The `ensures` contract lets lemmas reason about bounds without knowing the implementation.
Replaces Alloy's axiomatic `one sig DayMap { of: Timestamp -> Timezone -> one Day }` pattern.

Lemmas prove properties of the axioms:

```dafny
lemma UtcPreservesDay(utcDay: Day)
  ensures localDay(utcDay, 0) == utcDay
{ }

lemma LargerOffsetNeverEarlier(utcDay: Day, o1: TzOffset, o2: TzOffset)
  requires validOffset(o1) && validOffset(o2) && o1 <= o2
  ensures localDay(utcDay, o1) <= localDay(utcDay, o2)
{ }
```

## 32. Type-Dispatched Behavior

Different behavior per variant, dispatched via `match`:

```dafny
datatype ColumnKind = WithTZ | WithoutTZ

datatype StoredValue = StoredValue(colKind: ColumnKind, utcDay: Day, wallDay: Day)

function dateCast(v: StoredValue, sessionOffset: TzOffset): Day
  requires validOffset(sessionOffset)
{
  match v.colKind {
    case WithTZ => localDay(v.utcDay, sessionOffset)
    case WithoutTZ => v.wallDay
  }
}
```

Lemmas prove type-specific properties:

```dafny
lemma WithoutTZIgnoresSession(v: StoredValue, o1: TzOffset, o2: TzOffset)
  requires v.colKind == WithoutTZ
  requires validOffset(o1) && validOffset(o2)
  ensures dateCast(v, o1) == dateCast(v, o2)
{ }
```

This pattern models any entity with variant-dependent semantics: DB column types,
serialization formats, encryption modes, API response types.

## 33. Wire Format Encoding/Decoding

Model external data formats and verify codec correctness:

```dafny
datatype WireTimestamp = WireTimestamp(utcDay: Day)

function correctDecode(t: WireTimestamp): Day { t.utcDay }

function brokenDecode(t: WireTimestamp, offset: TzOffset): Day
  requires validOffset(offset)
{ localDay(t.utcDay, offset) }  // bug: double-converts already-local data
```

Prove the bug exists for specific inputs:

```dafny
lemma BrokenDecoderWrongForEast(t: WireTimestamp, offset: TzOffset)
  requires validOffset(offset) && offset >= 12
  ensures brokenDecode(t, offset) != t.utcDay
{
  assert dayShift(offset) == 1;  // hint: shift is +1 for far-east
}
```

This pattern catches encoding/decoding bugs where data passes through a pipeline that
misinterprets its format (wire-format vs DB storage, local time vs UTC).

## 34. Effect Bag / Metric Aggregation

Model typed contributions to a metric instead of raw integer accumulation:

```dafny
datatype Intensity = NoEffect | SmallEffect | MediumEffect | LargeEffect

datatype Reading = Reading(sensorOffset: TzOffset, utcDay: Day, intensity: Intensity)

predicate activates(r: Reading) { r.intensity != NoEffect }

function readingLocalDay(r: Reading): Day
  requires validOffset(r.sensorOffset)
{ localDay(r.utcDay, r.sensorOffset) }

predicate contributes(r: Reading, targetDay: Day)
  requires validOffset(r.sensorOffset)
{ activates(r) && readingLocalDay(r) == targetDay }
```

Prove cross-timezone divergence:

```dafny
lemma CrossTZDisjointDays(r1: Reading, r2: Reading)
  requires validOffset(r1.sensorOffset) && validOffset(r2.sensorOffset)
  requires r1.sensorOffset >= 12 && r2.sensorOffset <= -12
  requires r1.utcDay == r2.utcDay
  ensures readingLocalDay(r1) != readingLocalDay(r2)
{
  assert dayShift(r1.sensorOffset) == 1;
  assert dayShift(r2.sensorOffset) == -1;
}
```

This pattern avoids integer overflow while proving properties about aggregation windows.

## 35. Sliding Window with Offset

Verify which records fall inside or outside a time-based window under timezone shifts:

```dafny
predicate inWindow(r: Reading, targetDay: Day, windowSize: nat)
  requires validOffset(r.sensorOffset)
{
  var ld := readingLocalDay(r);
  targetDay - windowSize as int <= ld && ld <= targetDay + windowSize as int
}

lemma TimezoneCanBreakWindow(r: Reading, targetDay: Day)
  requires validOffset(r.sensorOffset) && r.sensorOffset >= 12
  requires r.utcDay == targetDay
  ensures !inWindow(r, targetDay, 0)
{
  assert dayShift(r.sensorOffset) == 1;
  // readingLocalDay(r) == targetDay + 1, outside [targetDay, targetDay]
}
```

Catches off-by-one and boundary-shift bugs in window-based attribution, billing cycles,
retention periods.

## 36. Pipeline DAG with Dependencies

Model multi-step pipelines as steps producing/consuming artifacts:

```dafny
predicate stepRequires(s: Step, a: Artifact): bool {
  match s {
    case S1_Trigger     => false  // no inputs
    case S2_Validate    => a == RawData
    case S3_Enrich      => a == Validated || a == RawData
    case S4_Index       => a == Enriched
    case S5_Report      => a == IndexData || a == Enriched
  }
}

// THE KEY LEMMA: no step uses artifacts from the future
lemma DependenciesSatisfied(s: Step, a: Artifact)
  requires stepRequires(s, a)
  ensures stepAtOrBefore(producedBy(a), s)
{ }

lemma AllDependenciesSatisfied()
  ensures forall s: Step, a: Artifact ::
    stepRequires(s, a) ==> stepAtOrBefore(producedBy(a), s)
{
  forall s: Step, a: Artifact | stepRequires(s, a)
    ensures stepAtOrBefore(producedBy(a), s)
  {
    DependenciesSatisfied(s, a);
  }
}
```

The forall dispatch pattern (see pattern 44) proves the property for every (Step, Artifact) pair.

## 37. Artifact Versioning & Staleness

Track mutable artifacts that get overwritten by multiple steps:

```dafny
datatype ArtifactVersion = ArtifactVersion(artifact: Artifact, writtenBy: Step, version: nat)

predicate isStale(consumer: Step, art: Artifact, v1: ArtifactVersion, v2: ArtifactVersion) {
  v1.artifact == art && v2.artifact == art &&
  v1.version < v2.version &&
  stepBefore(v1.writtenBy, consumer) &&
  stepBefore(v2.writtenBy, consumer)
}
```

A consumer sees stale data when a newer version exists from an earlier step. This pattern
is essential for pipelines with caches, indices, or snapshot artifacts.

## 38. Proof of Work (Evidence Tracking)

Enforce that verification steps produce specific evidence — prevents hollow "all passed" outputs:

```dafny
datatype ProofOfWork = ProofOfWork(
  step: Step,
  requiresCheckResults: bool,
  requiresScenarioTrace: bool,
  requiresCounterexplanation: bool
)

predicate proofOfWorkSatisfied(
  pow: ProofOfWork,
  hasChecks: bool,
  hasTraces: bool,
  hasExplanation: bool
) {
  (!pow.requiresCheckResults || hasChecks) &&
  (!pow.requiresScenarioTrace || hasTraces) &&
  (!pow.requiresCounterexplanation || hasExplanation)
}
```

Valuable for AI/LLM pipelines where intermediate verification can produce plausible
but ungrounded reports.

## 39. Resolved Choice (OR-Dependency)

Model "needs A or B" as a decision that resolves before the step runs:

```dafny
datatype RuntimeOption = UseLocalJava | UseDocker

predicate runtimeDependency(choice: RuntimeOption, a: Artifact): bool {
  match choice {
    case UseLocalJava => a == RunScript || a == LocalJava
    case UseDocker    => a == RunScript || a == DockerEngine
  }
}
```

The choice is a value, not a runtime branch. Lemmas can prove properties for each option
independently. Replaces the need for set-level OR in dependency relations.

## 40. Empty-Body Lemma

When the predicate is defined by exhaustive pattern matching, the lemma body can be empty —
Dafny evaluates all cases automatically:

```dafny
lemma NoCancelledShipment(o: Order)
  requires ValidOrder(o)
  requires o.status == Cancelled
  ensures o.previousStatus != Shipped
{ }
```

The verifier unfolds `ValidOrder(o)` and `ValidTransition(o.previousStatus, Cancelled)`,
checks all cases where `to == Cancelled`, and confirms none have `from == Shipped`.

This is the most common proof pattern in Dafny — if your definitions are complete, most
lemmas prove themselves.

## 41. Witness Construction

Help the SMT solver with existentials by providing explicit values:

```dafny
lemma UpgradePreservesUniqueness()
{
  var u := User(0, false);
  var p := Plan(0, true);
  var s := Subscription(0, 0, SubActive, false, PlatformA(0));
  var st := SystemState([u], [p], [s]);

  // Guide solver with intermediate assertions
  assert planPublished(st, 0);
  assert ValidState(st);
}
```

Without the explicit construction, the solver may timeout trying to find a satisfying
assignment. Intermediate `assert` statements break the proof into steps the solver can handle.

## 42. Contrapositive Restatement

Prove the contrapositive of an invariant by restating it as a lemma:

```dafny
// Invariant: live status implies not obsolete
// Contrapositive: obsolete implies not live status
lemma ObsoleteIsNeverLive(st: SystemState, subIdx: int)
  requires ValidState(st)
  requires 0 <= subIdx < |st.subs|
  requires st.subs[subIdx].obsolete
  ensures st.subs[subIdx].status != SubActive
  ensures st.subs[subIdx].status != SubInactive
  ensures st.subs[subIdx].status != SubCanceled
{ }
```

Empty body — the verifier recognizes this as the contrapositive of `LiveStatusImpliesLive`
from `ValidState`.

## 43. Assert Hint for SMT Guidance

When the solver needs help, add `assert` statements as intermediate proof steps:

```dafny
lemma BrokenDecoderWrongForEast(t: WireTimestamp, offset: TzOffset)
  requires validOffset(offset) && offset >= 12
  ensures brokenDecode(t, offset) != t.utcDay
{
  assert dayShift(offset) == 1;  // hint: tell solver what dayShift evaluates to
  // now solver can see: brokenDecode(t, offset) = t.utcDay + 1 != t.utcDay
}
```

Each `assert` creates a sub-goal the solver proves independently, then uses as a known fact
for subsequent goals. Use sparingly — too many hints make proofs fragile.

## 44. Exhaustive Forall Dispatch

Prove a universally quantified property by dispatching to a per-case lemma:

```dafny
lemma AllDependenciesSatisfied()
  ensures forall s: Step, a: Artifact ::
    stepRequires(s, a) ==> stepAtOrBefore(producedBy(a), s)
{
  forall s: Step, a: Artifact | stepRequires(s, a)
    ensures stepAtOrBefore(producedBy(a), s)
  {
    DependenciesSatisfied(s, a);  // per-case lemma
  }
}
```

The `forall` block inside the lemma body is Dafny's way of proving a universally quantified
postcondition. Each iteration calls a helper lemma that handles one (s, a) pair.

## 45. Gap Assertion (Expected Failure)

Document known design gaps as lemmas that would fail if uncommented:

```dafny
// This lemma would FAIL if uncommented — proves a design gap exists.
// ApprovalRequest template sends CtaApprove to all roles,
// but only Manager/Admin can approve. A Viewer receiving CtaApprove
// would see a dead button.
//
// lemma AllCtasValid_EXPECTED_FAIL()
//   ensures forall tmpl, cta, r, s ::
//     templateTriggeredInState(tmpl, s) &&
//     templateHasCta(tmpl, cta, r) ==>
//     ctaAvailable(cta, r, s)
// { }  // WOULD FAIL: templateHasCta sends CtaApprove to Viewer

// The fix: filter CTAs by role capability in templateHasCta
```

Gap assertions are valuable for: proving a bug exists (concrete evidence for stakeholders),
validating a fix (uncomment after fixing — it should pass), documenting known limitations.

## 46. Equivalence Classes

Replace continuous values with discrete behavior-triggering classes:

```dafny
datatype AmountClass = UnderThreshold | MidRange | OverThreshold

datatype Invoice = Invoice(amount: AmountClass, status: InvoiceStatus, approvedBy: set<Role>)

predicate validApproval(i: Invoice) {
  i.status == Approved ==>
    ((i.amount == UnderThreshold && Reviewer in i.approvedBy) ||
     (i.amount == MidRange && (Reviewer in i.approvedBy || Admin in i.approvedBy)) ||
     (i.amount == OverThreshold && Reviewer in i.approvedBy && Finance in i.approvedBy))
}

lemma DualApprovalForLargeInvoices(i: Invoice)
  requires validApproval(i)
  requires i.status == Approved && i.amount == OverThreshold
  ensures |i.approvedBy| >= 2
{ }
```

Dafny proves this for ALL inputs — no scope bound needed. The solver checks every
class-role combination exhaustively. Use when behavior depends on range membership,
not exact values.
